To track mouse movement and change the background color of an HTML document using JavaScript, you can use the following code:

HTML:
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Mouse Tracking</title>
</head>
<body onmousemove="trackMouse(event)">
	<h1>Move your mouse to change the background color</h1>
	<p>Mouse position: <span id="mousePosition"></span></p>
	<script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
JavaScript (in the "script.js" file):
```csharp
function trackMouse(event) {
  // Get the current mouse position
  var x = event.clientX;
  var y = event.clientY;

  // Update the HTML element that displays the mouse position
  document.getElementById("mousePosition").innerHTML = x + ", " + y;

  // Change the background color based on the mouse position
  var red = x % 256;
  var green = y % 256;
  var blue = (x + y) % 256;
  document.body.style.backgroundColor = "rgb(" + red + ", " + green + ", " + blue + ")";
}
```
In this example, the `onmousemove` attribute is attached to the `body` element to track mouse movement. When the mouse is moved, the `trackMouse` function is called with the `event` object as a parameter. This function gets the current mouse position from the `clientX` and `clientY` properties of the event object, updates an HTML element to display the mouse position, and changes the background color of the `body` element based on the mouse position.

The `red`, `green`, and `blue` variables are calculated using the mouse position and the modulo operator to keep the values within the range of 0 to 255. The `rgb()` CSS function is then used to set the background color of the `body` element to the calculated values.

Note that this is just an example and the actual implementation can be customized as per the requirements.

HTML and CSS are two technologies that work together to create visually appealing and interactive web pages. Here's an example of a simple HTML document with some CSS styling:

HTML:
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Web Page</title>
	<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
	<header>
		<h1>Welcome to My Web Page</h1>
		<nav>
			<ul>
				<li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
				<li><a href="#">About</a></li>
				<li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
			</ul>
		</nav>
	</header>
	<main>
		<section>
			<h2>About Me</h2>
			<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed commodo, velit sed convallis vestibulum, sem nisi elementum lectus, ac finibus neque mauris et nunc.</p>
		</section>
		<section>
			<h2>My Hobbies</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Reading</li>
				<li>Hiking</li>
				<li>Playing video games</li>
			</ul>
		</section>
	</main>
	<footer>
		<p>&copy; 2023 My Web Page</p>
	</footer>
</body>
</html>
```
CSS (in the "styles.css" file):
```css
body {
	font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
	background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

header {
	background-color: #333;
	color: #fff;
	padding: 20px;
}

nav ul {
	list-style-type: none;
	margin: 0;
	padding: 0;
}

nav li {
	display: inline-block;
	margin-right: 20px;
}

nav a {
	color: #fff;
	text-decoration: none;
}

main {
	max-width: 800px;
	margin: 0 auto;
	padding: 20px;
}

section {
	margin-bottom: 30px;
	border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
	padding-bottom: 20px;
}

h1, h2 {
	margin: 0;
}

footer {
	background-color: #333;
	color: #fff;
	padding: 10px;
	text-align: center;
}
```
In this example, the HTML document contains a header with a navigation bar, two sections of content, and a footer. The CSS file contains styles that modify the font, background color, and layout of the HTML document.

For example, the `body` element has a background color of `#f0f0f0`, the `header` element has a background color of `#333` and a text color of `#fff`, and the `nav` element has no bullet points and inline-block display. Additionally, the `main` element has a maximum width of `800px`, centered with `margin: 0 auto`, and padding of `20px`. The `footer` element has a background color of `#333`, a text color of `#fff`, and is centered with `text-align: center`.
